---
title: At What Time?
description: Learn to ask about and tell time, and talk about when things happen
level: elementary
time: 20 minutes
---

# Grammar: Telling Time

## Saying the Time

Use "es la" for 1:00 and "son las" for all other hours. Add minutes with "y" (and) or subtract with "menos" (minus).

Es la una.
  It's one o'clock.

Son las tres.
  It's three o'clock.

Son las diez y cuarto.
  It's ten fifteen.

Son las ocho y media.
  It's eight thirty.

Son las cinco menos diez.
  It's ten to five. (4:50)

## Morning, Afternoon, or Night

Spanish does not use a.m. or p.m. Instead, add "de la mañana" (morning), "de la tarde" (afternoon), or "de la noche" (night) after the time to be clear. Use "de la tarde" from around noon until sunset, and "de la noche" after dark.

Son las nueve de la mañana.
  It's 9 a.m. (nine in the morning)

Son las nueve de la noche.
  It's 9 p.m. (nine at night)

Son las tres de la tarde.
  It's 3 p.m. (three in the afternoon)

Es la una de la mañana.
  It's 1 a.m. (one in the morning)

Son las doce del día.
  It's noon. (twelve midday)

Son las doce de la noche.
  It's midnight. (twelve at night)

## Asking About Time

Use "¿A qué hora...?" to ask when something happens. The answer uses "a la" (for 1:00) or "a las" (for other hours).

¿A qué hora es la clase?
  What time is the class?

A las nueve de la mañana.
  At nine in the morning.

¿A qué hora llegas?
  What time do you arrive?

# Vocabulary: Telling Time

la hora
  the time / the hour
  [lah OH-rah]

en punto
  on the dot / sharp
  [ehn POON-toh]

y media
  half past / thirty
  [ee MEH-dee-ah]

y cuarto
  quarter past / fifteen
  [ee KWAHR-toh]

menos cuarto
  quarter to / forty-five
  [MEH-nohs KWAHR-toh]

de la mañana
  in the morning (a.m.)
  [deh lah mah-NYAH-nah]

de la tarde
  in the afternoon (p.m.)
  [deh lah TAHR-deh]

de la noche
  in the evening / at night (p.m.)
  [deh lah NOH-cheh]

el mediodía
  noon
  [ehl meh-dee-oh-DEE-ah]

la medianoche
  midnight
  [lah meh-dee-ah-NOH-cheh]

# Vocabulary: Daily Schedule

la cita
  the appointment
  [lah SEE-tah]

la clase
  the class
  [lah KLAH-seh]

la junta
  the meeting
  [lah HOON-tah]

la comida
  lunch (the main meal)
  [lah koh-MEE-dah]

temprano
  early
  [tehm-PRAH-noh]

tarde
  late
  [TAHR-deh]

a tiempo
  on time
  [ah tee-EHM-poh]

# Vocabulary: Street Time Talk (Northern Mexico)

¿A qué horas?
  What time? (casual — uses plural 'horas')
  [ah keh OH-rahs]

ahorita
  right now / in a bit (flexible — could mean either)
  [ah-oh-REE-tah]

al rato
  in a while / later
  [ahl RAH-toh]

ya merito
  almost / any minute now
  [yah meh-REE-toh]

tempranito
  nice and early (diminutive)
  [tehm-prah-NEE-toh]

Se me hizo tarde.
  I ran late. / Time got away from me.
  [seh meh EE-soh TAHR-deh]

¡Ya voy!
  I'm on my way! / Coming!
  [yah boy]

¿A qué horas caes?
  What time are you showing up?
  [ah keh OH-rahs KAH-ehs]

# Phrases: Asking and Telling Time

¿Qué hora es?
  What time is it?
  [keh OH-rah ehs]

¿A qué hora es...?
  What time is...?
  [ah keh OH-rah ehs]
  > ¿A qué hora es la junta?

Es a las...
  It's at...
  [ehs ah lahs]
  > Es a las dos de la tarde.

Tengo una cita a las...
  I have an appointment at...
  [TEHN-goh OO-nah SEE-tah ah lahs]
  > Tengo una cita a las diez.

Llego a las...
  I arrive at...
  [YEH-goh ah lahs]

¿A qué hora te levantas?
  What time do you get up?
  [ah keh OH-rah teh leh-BAHN-tahs]

¿A qué hora sales del trabajo?
  What time do you leave work?
  [ah keh OH-rah SAH-lehs dehl trah-BAH-hoh]

